<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Construction of Expressways Increased </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0501114594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1126 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0501114594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 5 (XINHUA) -- With the inauguration 
of the Jinan-Qingdao expressway a few days ago in east China's 
Shandong Province, China last year extended the length of its 
expressways to 1,293 km, according to the "CHINA COMMUNICATIONS" 
[ZHONGGUO JIAOTONG] newspaper. 
  The Ministry of Communications decided to construct 
expressways at the beginning of the 1980s when the country's 
economy began to boom. 
  Building of the first one started in 1984 in northeast 
China, 
from Shenyang to Dalian. After its completion in 1990, the 
375-km- long road brought with it great economic and social 
efficiency. 
  The ministry made a long-term program in 1988 to build a 
national highway network in several five-year plan periods. 
Since then, some expressways have been built from Guangzhou to 
Foshan, Xian to Lintong, Beijing to Tianjin and Beijing to 
Shijiazhuang. 
  Several expressways from Shanghai to Nanjing, Guangzhou to 
Shenzhen and Hangzhou to Ningbo are now under construction. 
  These expressways have given an impetus to the local 
economic 
development along these roads. Some industrial zones and 
economic development areas have arisen along the routes. 

</TEXT>

