<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beijing To Expand International Agrotechnical Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0601141194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1241 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0601141194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 6 (XINHUA) -- China has set up 
exchange and cooperation relations in agricultural science and 
technology with 141 countries and international organizations 
including the World Bank, the United Nations Food and 
Agriculture Organization and the World Food Program. 
  According to the Ministry of Agriculture, over the past 15 
years, China has introduced a batch of programs of agricultural 
technology involving chicken raising, artificial insemination of 
livestock, agricultural remote-sensing and plastic sheets on 
fields. 
  The ministry alone invited more than 2,500 experts from 
overseas in the period and, plus the number of foreign experts 
invited by provinces, the figure is estimated to be more than 
10,000. 
  The World Food Program helped 30 provinces, regions and 
municipalities in the country in setting up 55 grain production 
project worth more than 700 million U.S. dollars. 
  The World Bank also provided loans of 850 million U.S. 
dollars for China's 16 agricultural projects. 
  Statistics show that China now has more than 400 
agricultural 
projects which are funded by foreign loans totaling 2.6 billion 
U.S. dollars. 

</TEXT>

