<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Wants `Partnership' With NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0601040894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0222 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0601040894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, January 5 (XINHUA) -- Russian Defence 
Minister Pavel Grachev said today that his country wishes to 
develop a partnership with the North Atlantic Treaty 
Organization (NATO) on the basis of extensive political contacts 
and policy and action coordination. 
  Meeting with two visiting U.S. senators, Grachev said that 
in 
its security concept of partnership for peace, NATO should take 
into account the interests of all countries instead of its 
member states only, the INTERFAX News Agency reported. 
  Russia, which used to lead the Warsaw Pact nations against 
NATO during the Cold War, has become deeply concerned over the 
attempts of some of its former partners to join NATO. Russia 
insisted that NATO should first weaken its role as a 
political-military bloc. 
  To ease Russia's anxiety, the United States has said that it 
opposes NATO's immediate acceptance of any East European nation. 
  In his meeting with the U.S. senators, Grachev also said 
Russia has given up its former promise of not using nuclear 
weapons first because other nuclear powers have not done so. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

