<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japanese Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata's Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Discusses Bilateral Ties </H4>
<F P=102> OW0701135694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1347 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0701135694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, January 7 (XINHUA) -- Japanese Deputy Premier 
and Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata said here today that 
Sino-Japanese cooperation in the coming years should be 
future-oriented and conducive to world peace and prosperity. 
  In an exclusive interview with XINHUA, Hata noted that 
friendly Sino-Japanese relations, which were normalized in 1972, 
have entered a new phase and should be broadened for the benefit 
of the international community. 
  Hata, who leaves for Beijing tomorrow on an official visit, 
reiterated Japan's support for China's reform and modernization 
drive. 
  "A long-term and sustainable economic development in China 
is 
of vital importance," he observed. "China's bid for a socialist 
market economy, if it succeeds, will have a significant bearing 
on the global economy, and on peace and stability in Asia and 
the world at large." 
  He discounted the threat of China's military buildup, saying 
China will not "go for big-military power status" despite its 
efforts toward arms modernization. 
  On the question of Tokyo-Taiwan ties, the foreign minister 
said that the Japanese Government has been committed to 
maintaining only non-official contact with Taiwan since 1972. 
  Although there are divergent views on the issue in his 
country, Hata noted that Japan's Taiwan policy is unchanged, and 
promised that it will remain so in the future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

