<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Official on Cutting Tariffs in U.S. Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0701093494 Taipei Voice of Free China in English 0200 GMT 
7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0701093494 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei Voice of Free China </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News" program] </F>
  [Text] A top ROC [Republic of China] trade negotiator has 
said that if Washington and Taipei can reach preliminary 
agreement on tariff cuts when they meet this month, Taiwan will 
be prepared to lower some of them by April or May for the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. 
  (Huang Yen-tao), director general of the Board of Foreign 
Trade and the government's chief trade negotiator, pledged not 
to give in easily to Washington's demand when he meets with U.S. 
negotiators on January 19. 
  The U.S. Trade Representative Office gave the Board of 
Foreign Trade a list of 2,785 products last year in November on 
which the U.S. [words indistinct] wants Taiwan to cut trade 
tariffs on as a prerequisite for its entry into the GATT. Of 
the 2,785 products, Taipei was given a December 3 deadline to 
lower tariffs by 50 percent on 699 items. Among the 699 items 
she mentioned in the ultimatum, 514 were auto and industrial 
manufacturing products. Taipei rejected Washington's request in 
December last year but agreed to discuss the issue in bilateral 
tariffs negotiation early this year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

