<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hainan To Accelerate Property Rights Reform </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0601080094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0725 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0601080094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Haikou, January 6 (XINHUA) -- Hainan Province, 
China's largest special economic zone, will accelerate the 
reform of property rights this year to meet the demand of a 
market economy. 
  According to Chi Fulin with the Provincial Office for 
Economic Restructuring, since 1988 when Hainan was designated a 
special economic zone, a market economy has taken shape in line 
with a new social security system. 
  However, the official said, the reform of property rights 
has 
become a pressing need nowadays, and a lot of state enterprises 
are far from efficient. By the end of last year, 30 percent of 
the province's state-run industrial enterprises were operating 
at a loss, while 70 percent of its commercial and trading firms 
did not make profits. 
  The province will place more emphasis on transforming its 
state enterprises into share-holding companies. So far Hainan 
has approved the setting up of 126 share-holding companies with 
total assets of more than 20 billion yuan. 
  The province will also foster the transaction of various 
property rights concerning stocks, patents and fixed assets, the 
officials said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

