<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hainan Sees Industry Output Exceed Agriculture </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0601015494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0130 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0601015494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Haikou, January 6 (XINHUA) -- Southern China's 
Hainan Province saw its industrial output value exceed that of 
agriculture last year for the first time in the history of this, 
China's largest special economic zone. 
  Since its establishment as a province more than five years 
ago, Hainan, once a remote and backward region, has gained 
momentum for a sound economic development and improvement of its 
economic structure. 
  The total industrial output of the province in 1993 reached 
9.3 billion yuan-worth, with a growth of about 28.9 percent over 
the previous year. The agricultural output value was 8.4 
billion, an increase of 6.2 percent. 
  Industrial enterprises around the whole province flourished 
last year. The automobile and motorcycle industries recorded 
production increases of 446.7 percent and 460.5 percent, 
respectively. 
  Remarkable growth was also achieved in the beverage, pig 
iron 
and cement industries. 
  Last year the provincial government earmarked 1.5 billion 
yuan for major industrial construction projects in order to lay 
a firm foundation for further development. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-44729 </DOCNO>
