<F P=100> Southwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tibet To Open Stock Exchange </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0501125794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1235 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0501125794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lhasa, January 5 (XINHUA) -- Tibetans will soon be 
able to experience all the excitement and frustration brought by 
a stock market as Tibet's first stock exchange is expected to 
open in the middle of this month in this capital of the 
autonomous region. 
  President of the Tibetan trust and investment corporation 
Chen Irui said that satellite communications will link the 
Tibetan trading house and the stock exchanges in Shanghai and 
Shenzhen. The computer system in the Lhasa stock exchange is 
already for operation. 
  Entrusted by the autonomous regional government, Chen's 
company is responsible for the establishment of Tibet's first 
stock exchange. Like many other undertakings, the establishment 
of Tibet's stock market also gained support of other regions of 
the country. 
  The company is now the 381st member of the Shanghai stock 
exchange, which has donated a full set of equipment to the 
Tibetan exchange and helped in its installation, Chen said. 
  The Tibetan exchange will also be the first in China to have 
two- way communication links with the Shenzhen stock exchange, 
Chen said. 
  He added that the four-star Tibetan hotel in Chengdu, 
capital 
of Sichuan Province, has applied to be listed. If the 
application is granted, it will be the first shareholding 
company in Tibet. 
  Chen stressed that what matters is not that stocks are 
available to Tibetans, but that Tibet is keeping pace with other 
Chinese regions in establishing a modern banking and investment 
system, and a modern enterprise system. 
  As more Tibetan companies are considering adopting 
shareholding systems, stock trading faces a bright future in 
Tibet, the Chen said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

