<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Draft Regulations on Airport Corporation Discussed </TI></H3>
<H4>   Zhang Junsheng Calls UK `Unreasonable' </H4>
<F P=102> OW0701144294 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0827 
GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0701144294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, 7 Jan (XINHUA) -- Zhang Junsheng, deputy 
director of XINHUA's Hong Kong branch, said that the British 
Hong Kong Government is unreasonable for refusing to send an 
official to explain the new airport issue to the Preliminary 
Working Committee [PWC] of the Hong Kong Special Administrative 
Region [HKSAR] Preparatory Committee. 
  The British Hong Kong Government, in the "White Paper on the 
Draft Regulations on the New Airport Corporation" it publicized 
on 3 January, proposes that the current provisional airport 
administrative office be reorganized to become a commercial 
corporation. Because of this, during its third meeting, the 
Economic Subcommittee under the PWC of the HKSAR Preparatory 
Committee requested the British Hong Kong authorities to send an 
official to the PWC to explain the draft regulations on the new 
airport in Hong Kong. But the British Hong Kong Government 
openly rejected the request. Chen-Fang Ansheng, chief secretary 
of the Hong Kong Government, said that there is "no need" for 
the Hong Kong Government to send anyone to Beijing to explain to 
the PWC the draft regulations because "the available channels 
are sufficient." 
  In this connection, Zhang Junsheng indicated that because 
the 
issue of the new airport in Hong Kong is a matter that will 
extend beyond 1997, it should be properly settled by China and 
Britain through consultations. He said that the PWC has the 
responsibility to study matters relevant to Hong Kong's smooth 
transition and that its invitation to Hong Kong Government 
officials to explain the draft regulations is something that 
they should do because it is for the sake of Hong Kong's smooth 
transition. He reiterated that the Chinese Government sincerely 
hopes to cooperate with the British Hong Kong Government. 

</TEXT>

