<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Draft Regulations on Airport Corporation Discussed </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hong Kong Urged To Explain Bill </H4>
<F P=102> OW0701143494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1425 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0701143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, January 7 (XINHUA) -- China has accused 
the British Hong Kong authorities of lacking sincerity in 
cooperation with the Chinese Mainland by refusing to explain the 
newly- formulated airport bill to Beijing. 
  The mainland's request to invite a Hong Kong Government 
civil 
servant to Beijing to explain the airport management plan was 
advanced at a meeting attended by Chinese officials and 
Preliminary Working Committee (PWC) for the Preparatory 
Committee of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region. 
  However, the request was immediately turned down by the 
British Hong Kong authorities on an excuse of there is no need 
to establish another channel of communication. 
  Responding to the refusal from the Hong Kong Government, 
Zhang Junsheng, deputy director of the XINHUA NEWS AGENCY Hong 
Kong branch, said the Hong Kong Government failed to offer any 
convincing argument for the refusal. 
  Construction of the Hong Kong new airport is one of the 
matters stretching the change-over of power in 1997. Therefore 
the draft airport corporation bill should be discussed through 
consultation between the Chinese and British Government, Zhang 
said. 
  The PWC shoulders the responsibility of studying issues 
relating to the smooth transfer of power in Hong Kong. It is 
logical for them to invite an official from the Hong Kong 
Government to explain the airport bill, he added. 
  Zhang stated that the draft airport corporation bill was 
published under the demand of the Chinese side to seek opinions 
from local residents. 
  He said he is expecting that the current invitation of 
public 
opinions would be done in real earnest instead of making a 
gesture. 

</TEXT>

