<DATE1>  7 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lu Ping Explains Right of Abode in Hong Kong </TI></H3>
<H4>   Policy To Be `Flexible' </H4>
<F P=102> HK0701045294 Hong Kong THE STANDARD in English 7 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK0701045294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong THE STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Rain Ren in Beijing, Michael Smith and M. Y. Sung] </F>
  [Text] China has moved to allay fears that up to 400,000 
Hong Kong Chinese with foreign passports will not be able to 
resettle in Hong Kong after 1997. The State Council's Hong Kong 
and Macao Affairs Office director Lu Ping said yesterday that 
while it was likely they would retain the right of abode, they 
would lose their Chinese citizenship under China's long-standing 
policy of opposing dual-citizenship. 
  Lu said the issue needed further study in the Sino-British 
Joint Liaison Group (JLG) to protect the residence rights of 
Hong Kong Chinese. "If those people cannot keep their right of 
abode in Hong Kong after obtaining foreign passports, we have to 
study under which circumstances their right of abode can be 
retained," Lu said. "Generally speaking, our policy on this 
issue is flexible and we will try to deal with it flexibly." 
  The Hong Kong government warned yesterday that up to 400,000 
Hong Kong Chinese would not be able to retain their permanent 
residence status under the Basic Law. It also said between 
10,000 and 20,000 non-Chinese, mainly Indians and Pakistanis 
holding British Dependent Territories Citizen (BDTC) passports, 
would also be denied the right to live here under the Basic Law. 
  Lu said China would try to ensure Chinese citizens born in 
Hong Kong would not need to re-apply for residence if they 
returned. "Such people, when they return to Hong Kong, do not 
need go through any procedure," he said. Non-Chinese who had 
lived in Hong Kong for at least seven years and regarded the 
territory as their permanent residential place would also be 
granted right of abode after 1997, Lu said. But he warned their 
right of abode would be "examined" if they returned to live in 
their mother country. "Such a move means that they do not 
consider Hong Kong their permanent residential place and 
therefore there is no point for them to continue to enjoy the 
right of abode," Lu said. 
  However, it is not yet known whether the seven-year 
criterion 
should apply to Hong Kong Chinese with foreign passports. Rita 
Fan, leader of the Social Order Group of the Preliminary Working 
Committee, also said Hong Kong Chinese with foreign passports 
would retain the right of abode after China took over. She said 
the important thing was to define the conditions listed under 
Article 24 of the Basic Law. 
  The PWC Social Order Group will meet in Beijing next week to 
study this issue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

