<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   Satellite Monitoring System To Forecast Snowstorms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0701021094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0132 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0701021094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lanzhou, January 7 (XINHUA) -- China has completed a 
new snow-monitoring system for pastoral areas. 
  The satellite monitoring system can forecast the possibility 
of disastrous snowstorms and estimate the damage that can 
result, through remote sensing techniques, over a vast pastoral 
area from western China's Tibet-Qinghai Plateau to the Greater 
Hinggan Mountains in northeast China. 
  Snow disasters cause heavy losses to livestock in northern 
China every year, sometimes as much as five percent of the total. 
  Scientists from the Lanzhou Institute of Glaciology and 
Cryopedology in northwest China's Gansu Province prepared the 
data for the satellite monitoring covering an area of about 
590,000 sq [square] km. 

</TEXT>

