<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Advanced' Production of Drill Bit Achieved </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0701094794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0836 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0701094794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tianjin, January 7 (XINHUA) -- A multi-blade drill 
bit invented 40 years ago by Ni Zhifu, now 61-year-old 
vice-chairman of the National People's Congress of China, is now 
being made more accurately by a computer-controlled machine. 
  Tianjin University recently developed the high-tech machine 
tool to make the bit, after decades in which this sophisticated 
cutter had been hand-made. 
  The machine tool developed by the university in north 
China's 
Tianjin city is among the most advanced ones in the world. It 
can make a bit that has different irregularly shaped blades. 
  According to a university official, the highly efficient bit 
has been widely used in machine-making industry in the world. 
  Ni was then elected a model worker because of his invention, 
and later became the head of the All-China Federation of Trade 
Unions (ACFTU). 
  The official said that though the bit has been updated with 
different models in the past decades, the fact that it had to be 
hand-made caused problems in assuring uniform standards of 
quality. 
  The newly developed automatic machine tool has solved the 
problem. It uses a computer to control the making of bits. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

