<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Firms To Introduce Autonomous Wage Experiment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0701092194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0758 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0701092194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 7 (XINHUA) -- China is embarking on 
a trial reform of the wage system in 100 state-owned enterprises 
this year which will enable them to decide on their own staff's 
wages. 
  Meanwhile, in foreign-funded or privately-owned enterprises, 
the state will advocate a system of setting wage levels through 
collective negotiation or consultation. 
  In an interview with XINHUA, a high-ranking official with 
the 
state's Ministry of Labor said that the reform will focus on 
readjusting staff income structures in large and medium-sized 
enterprises with state ownership. 
  The reform will channel numerous employee subsidies and 
allowances, including housing subsidies, into their salaries. 
And the enterprises will be granted full decision-making powers 
in setting or increasing wages for their employees on the 
prerequisite that their wage increase rates do not exceed a rate 
representing economic efficiency. 
  According to the official, the enterprises chosen for trial 
wage reform will determine for themselves the number of 
employees needed, and managerial personnel in the enterprises 
will be salaried yearly under the system. 
  Along with the wage reform measures, the state will regulate 
and guide social distribution by setting minimum wage levels or 
issuing guidelines on wage increases. 
  The official noted that the present wage reform will also 
take into consideration the wage readjustment being conducted in 
government organizations or institutions. He said that wage 
increases in the enterprises should be made in light of economic 
efficiency and the cost of living index. 
  Meanwhile, the reform will also try to smooth out wage 
relations between enterprises and government institutions and 
between in- service staff and retired personnel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

