<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Reports on Electronics Industry Development </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0601153494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1408 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0601153494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 6 (XINHUA) -- The total value of 
China's electronics industry in 1993 reached a record 135 
billion yuan, a hefty increase of 24 percent over 1992. 
  The latest statistics from the Ministry of the Electronics 
Industry show that the total sales of the industry in 1993 came 
to 98 billion yuan-worth, an increase of 34 percent over 1992, 
while tax paid reached 7.2 billion yuan, a rise of 12 percent. 
  According to the ministry, products such as SPC [expansion 
not given] exchanges, telephones, fax machines, microcomputers 
and mobile communication products saw an average increase of 
more than 50 percent last year. 
  During the same period, further improvements have been made 
in the structure of products, while software and information 
services have undergone rapid development. 
  This development trend has become even more obvious in the 
coastal areas, such as Tianjin and Shanghai cities, and Jiangsu, 
Zhejiang, Fujian, Shandong and Guangdong Provinces, where the 
value of the electronics industry accounted for 62.7 percent of 
the country's total last year. 
  Shandong ranked first in China in terms of the development 
of 
its electronics industry, the ministry said. 
  The economic and technological co-operation between China's 
electronics industry and its foreign counterparts continues to 
expand, according to the ministry; the total export value of the 
industry last year increased by nearly 20 percent compared to 
the previous year. 
  Meanwhile, the number of foreign-funded major electronics 
projects has increased rapidly and they have become a major 
force in the industry, the ministry added. 

</TEXT>

