<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nongovernmental Technical Service Firms Increase </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0701121594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1047 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0701121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 7 (XINHUA) -- The number of non- 
governmental new and high technology enterprises run by 
scientists- turned-businessmen exceeded 40,000 by the end of 
1993, according to an official from the State Commission of 
Science and Technology. 
  At a press conference here today, Hui Yongzheng, 
vice-minister of the commission, said that over 10,000 such 
enterprises were set up over the past year. 
  High-tech enterprises refers to firms started by scientists 
which raise capital funds through non-governmental channels and 
enjoy independent management and hold sole responsibility for 
their own profits and losses. 
  For example, some of the country's best-known high-tech 
firms, such as Stone Company, Legend Group Corp., Beijing 
University Founder Co. Ltd. and Hope Computers Co. Ltd. are 
among these enterprises. 
  According to the Chinese official, the 40,000 
non-governmental firms, who in total have more than 600,000 
employees, hit a record profit of 25 billion yuan (2.9 billion 
U.S. dollars) last year. 
  He said that the businesses of these enterprises have 
extended to virtually all industries in the national economy 
while concentrating in technology-intensive industries including 
chemical industry, telecommunications, machinery, precision 
instruments, computers, building materials, medicines, 
biological products and environmental protection. 
  Hui noted that the average input in research and development 
has made up over 6 percent of these enterprises' total income 
and the scientific and technological employees have accounted 
for over 30 percent of their total staff. 
  According to Hui, China's large non-governmental scientific 
enterprises have got off to a good start in industrialization 
and internationalization of high technologies. 
  One example is that the Hope Computers Corporation under the 
Chinese Academy of Sciences, which was started by eight 
graduates ten years ago, now has the largest share of the 
country's sales of cad products. 
  The Legend Group Corp. now holds ten percent of the 
international market in the sales of QDI [expansion unknown] 
personnel computer cards. 
  "In the next two years, the Chinese Government will work out 
a series of policies, documents and regulations in order to help 
the non-governmental technological enterprises grow in a 
healthy, sustainable, rapid manner, bringing them into the 
international market in a big way," Hui said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

