<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Press Cancels Boycott </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0701015594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0102 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0701015594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, January 6 (XINHUA) -- Russian press today 
canceled a scheduled boycott after a government concession on a 
major hike of printing costs. 
  More than 20 Russian newspapers decided yesterday to stop 
publishing from January 11 to 17 when the new parliament opens 
its first session and U.S. President Bill Clinton visits Russia. 
  The move was designed to protest against a November 25 
government decree which would raise the printing costs by five 
times. 
  To avert the press revolt, Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin 
today held talks with the editors-in-chief of these newspapers 
and decided to suspend the decree. 

</TEXT>

